6 Conclusion.content:
We propose a general operator learner based on a simple attention mechanism. The network is versatile and is able to approximate both the PDE solution operator and the inverse coefficient identification operator. The evaluation accuracy on the benchmark problems surpasses the current best state-of-the-art operator learner Fourier Neural Operator (FNO) in \[ [57])\].
However, we acknowledge the limitation of this work: (i) similar to other operator learners, the subspace, on which we aim to learn the operator‚Äôs responses, may be infinite dimensional,
but the operator must exhibit certain low-dimensional attributes (e.g., smoothing property of the higher frequencies in GRF);
(ii) it is not efficient for the attention operator to be applied at the full resolution for a 2D problem, and this limits the approximation to a nonsmooth subset such as functions in L‚àûsuperscriptùêøL^{\\infty};
(iii) due to the order of the matrix product, the proposed linear variant of the scaled dot-product attention is non-causal thus can only apply to encoder-only applications.
